Note: Private methods in interfaces were introduced in Java 9.

1. What is a private method in an interface?

Answer:

A private method is a method declared with the private keyword inside an interface.
Introduced in Java 9.
Used to share common code between default and static methods.
It cannot be accessed outside the interface.

Example:

interface Demo {

    private void show() {
        System.out.println("Private Method");
    }

    default void display() {
        show();
    }
}
2. Why were private methods added to interfaces in Java 9?

Answer:

To reduce code duplication.
To reuse common logic inside default and static methods.
To improve code maintainability.
To hide implementation details.
3. Can we call private methods from outside the interface?

Answer:

No.
They can only be called from default, static, or other private methods within the same interface.
4. Can a private method be static or non-static?

Answer:

Yes.
Interface private methods can be:
private
private static

Example:

interface Demo {

    private void show() { }

    private static void display() { }
}
5. How do private methods help in code reusability inside interfaces?

Answer:

Common logic is written once.
Default and static methods can reuse it.
Avoids duplicate code.
Makes the interface easier to maintain.
Programs
1. Write an interface with one private static method and one default method calling it.
interface Demo {

    private static void message() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }

    default void show() {
        message();
    }
}

class Test implements Demo { }

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Test t = new Test();
        t.show();
    }
}

Output:

Hello
2. Demonstrate how private methods reduce code duplication in interfaces.
interface Demo {

    private void print() {
        System.out.println("Common Logic");
    }

    default void show() {
        print();
    }

    default void display() {
        print();
    }
}

class Test implements Demo { }

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Test t = new Test();

        t.show();
        t.display();
    }
}

